06117nam a22008655i 9781400830732DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092009nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008307327 a10.1515/97814008307322doi  a(DE-B1597)446989  a(OCoLC)979741901  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aK3943 .P65 2011 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a343.08704aThe Politics of Global Regulation /ced. by Ngaire Woods, Walter Mattli.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b12 line illus. 3 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE. In Whose Benefit? Explaining Regulatory Change in Global Politics -- tCHAPTER TWO. The Governance Triangle: Regulatory Standards Institutions and the Shadow of the State -- tCHAPTER THREE. Filling a Hole in Global Financial Governance? The Politics of Regulating Sovereign Debt Restructuring -- tCHAPTER FOUR. From State Responsibility to Individual Criminal Accountability: A New Regulatory Model for Core Human Rights Violations -- tCHAPTER FIVE. The Private Regulation of Global Corporate Conduct -- tCHAPTER SIX. Racing to the Top . . . at Last: The Regulation of Safety in Shipping -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Regulatory Shift: The Rise of Judicial Liberalization at the WTO -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. Economic Integration and Global Governance: Why So Little Supranationalism? -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRegulation by public and private organizations can be hijacked by special interests or small groups of powerful firms, and nowhere is this easier than at the global level. In whose interest is the global economy being regulated? Under what conditions can global regulation be made to serve broader interests? This is the first book to examine systematically how and why such hijacking or "regulatory capture" happens, and how it can be averted. Walter Mattli and Ngaire Woods bring together leading experts to present an analytical framework to explain regulatory outcomes at the global level and offer a series of case studies that illustrate the challenges of a global economy in which many institutions are less transparent and are held much less accountable by the media and public officials than are domestic institutions. They explain when and how global regulation falls prey to regulatory capture, yet also shed light on the positive regulatory changes that have occurred in areas including human rights, shipping safety, and global finance. This book is a wake-up call to proponents of network governance, self-regulation, and the view that technocrats should be left to regulate with as little oversight as possible. In addition to the editors, the contributors are Kenneth W. Abbott, Samuel Barrows, Judith L. Goldstein, Eric Helleiner, Miles Kahler, David A. Lake, Kathryn Sikkink, Duncan Snidal, Richard H. Steinberg, and David Vogel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aForeign trade regulation. 0aInternational economic integration. 0aInternational trade. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aAbbott, Kenneth W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrows, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldstein, Judith L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelleiner, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahler, Miles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLake, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMattli, Walte